In <catoD2oGuz.4B9@netcom.com>, cato@netcom.com  (Robert Whisler) writes:

>I installed IBMWORKS, and ran IWDEREG.CMD.  I really didn't see that much of
>a performance increase.

Did you shut down your machine after running IWDEREG.CMD?  It's like changing
config.sys you need to shutdown to complete Workplace Shell objects de-registration.

>I deleted IBMWORKS totally, and what a difference!  Now I can say OS/2 v3.0
>really warps.
>
>I think the problem is the .DLL files, which load into memory whether you run
>IWDEREG or not.  Those .DLL files, I understand, are pretty large.

This doesn't make sense if you ran IWDEREG.CMD and shutdown your PC, unless
your swap file is on the same drive as IBM Works and you don't have much free
space on the drive and the drive is fragmented.  In this case removing any un-wanted
programs will speed things up, co's on startup the swap file will create faster and
subsequent access to or the expansion of the swap file will be faster.

According our testing,  the performance slowdown has more to do with SOM 1
objects than memory.  We have tested the reported slowdown scenarios and we
were able to reproduce the slow down with SOM 1 objects but not with the new
SOM 2 objects regardless the memory configurations.  The slowdown does not
happen on every machines and on machines with less than 8MB memory it's
more likely to happen.   If you have not experienced any slowdown, you probably
should not worry about it.  If are experiening slowdown, running IWDEREG.CMD
(remember to shutdown afterwards) will unload the SOM 1 WPS objects and should
solve the slowdown problem and also give you back about 1MB of memory.  In any
case you will benefit from our SOM 2 WPS objects.  IBM will make them available
in the coming (when? sorry, please find out from IBM) Warp refresh.


Z. Zeng
Member of the IBM Works Development Team
Footprint Software Inc., Toronto
zzeng@footprint.com

Using IBM Works and Internet Connection from OS/2 Warp BonusPak and IBM
LAN server requester on a notebook with 12MB ram.
Slowdown? What slowdown?  :-)

